Great news — since you’re already using the folder mode (not --onefile), you’re halfway there. Here’s what’s happening and how to speed things up:
Why It’s Slow
PyInstaller apps on network drives are slow because on launch, Python needs to read hundreds of small .pyc, .dll, and .so files from the _internal/ folder — and each file read over a slow network link adds latency.

Solutions (Best to Easiest)
1. 🏆 Cache to Local Temp on Startup (Best Fix)
Wrap your app with a small launcher script that copies the folder to the local machine first, then runs it from there:

# launcher.py
import os, shutil, subprocess, sys, tempfile

src = os.path.dirname(os.path.abspath(__file__))  # network drive location
dst = os.path.join(tempfile.gettempdir(), "myapp_cache")

# Only re-copy if files changed (compare modified time of exe)
src_exe = os.path.join(src, "myapp.exe")
dst_exe = os.path.join(dst, "myapp.exe")

if not os.path.exists(dst_exe) or os.path.getmtime(src_exe) > os.path.getmtime(dst_exe):
    shutil.copytree(src, dst, dirs_exist_ok=True)

subprocess.run([dst_exe] + sys.argv[1:])


This copies once and caches — subsequent launches are near-instant as long as the exe hasn’t changed.

2. Zip the _internal Folder (PKG Archive)
PyInstaller supports loading from a .pkg zip archive. You can consolidate all the internal files into one large file — one big sequential read is faster than thousands of small reads over a network:

pyinstaller yourscript.py --collect-all yourpackage


Then in your .spec file:

exe = EXE(..., contents_directory='.')  # flattens layout (PyInstaller 6+)


Or use --contents-directory . flag to put everything next to the exe rather than in _internal/.

3. Exclude Unused Modules
Fewer files = faster load. Aggressively exclude what you don’t need in your .spec:

a = Analysis(
    ['script.py'],
    excludes=[
        'tkinter', 'unittest', 'email', 'html', 'http',
        'urllib', 'xml', 'pydoc', 'doctest', 'argparse',
        'difflib', 'multiprocessing'
    ],
)


4. Use UPX Compression
Reduces total file size (fewer bytes over the wire):

pyinstaller yourscript.py --upx-dir /path/to/upx


5. Pre-warm with a Shortcut (Quick Win)
If code changes are rare, just run the app once locally from the network path to let the OS file cache warm up. The second and subsequent launches on the same machine will be much faster until the cache is evicted.

Recommended Combo



|Scenario           |Recommendation                  |
|-------------------|--------------------------------|
|Files change rarely|Launcher script with local cache|
|Files change often |Exclude unused modules + UPX    |
|PyInstaller 6+     |`--contents-directory .` + UPX  |

The launcher cache approach (#1) will give you the most dramatic improvement with no rebuild required.​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​